1
00:00:02,056 --> 00:00:17,161
The manner in which the Four Noble Truths were formulated was that of the physicians of the time concerning any illness.

2
00:00:18,323 --> 00:00:27,338
Firstly the illness was described and named, the cause was then stated, then the prognosis or likely outcome of the disease, and finally the treatment.

3
00:00:28,077 --> 00:00:34,106
So if we were following the normal course, we should go on to the third noble truth, the truth of the end of suffering.

4
00:00:35,106 --> 00:00:46,404
But for clarity's sake, we shall instead go on to the treatment of our dis-ease, the fourth noble truth, in which the Buddha lays down the path that leads to the perfect cure for life's sufferings.

5
00:00:48,466 --> 00:00:55,957
This is how it is put in the first ever talk the Buddha gave after his enlightenment, the Discourse on the Turning of the Wheel of the Law.

6
00:00:57,405 --> 00:01:02,877
These two extremes, O disciples, should not be practiced by one who has gone forth from the world.

7
00:01:03,637 --> 00:01:04,500
What are these two?

8
00:01:05,641 --> 00:01:12,034
That which is to do with passions and pleasure, low, vulgar, coarse, ignoble and useless.

9
00:01:12,896 --> 00:01:17,945
And that which is to do with mortification, painful, ignoble and useless.

10
00:01:19,141 --> 00:01:32,156
Avoiding these two extremes, the Tathagata has attained the knowledge of the middle path, which gives perception and knowledge, and leads to peace, to insight, enlightenment and nirvana.

11
00:01:33,278 --> 00:01:35,161
What then is this middle path?

12
00:01:36,563 --> 00:01:46,515
It is the noble eightfold path, namely, right understanding, right intention, right speech, right action, right livelihood.

13
00:01:46,984 --> 00:01:50,670
right effort, right mindfulness and right concentration.

14
00:01:53,072 --> 00:02:06,572
Buddhism is often called the middle path or the middle way, that between self-indulgence governed by desire for pleasure and by the passions and self-mortification involving penances and self-torture.

15
00:02:07,953 --> 00:02:12,840
The path of self-indulgence is the way of those who believe happiness is to be found in pleasure.

16
00:02:13,360 --> 00:02:21,394
The path of mortification is the way of those who believe that the destruction of the physical appetites and desires leads to liberation.

17
00:02:22,877 --> 00:02:34,137
The middle path lies between these two in this sense, that bodily appetites are natural to human life, we need to eat, and our appetite depends on tasty food.

18
00:02:34,741 --> 00:02:45,090
However, once we begin to indulge these appetites indulge the delights of taste caring little for the body needs our appetites grow coarse and vulgar.

19
00:02:45,591 --> 00:02:46,611
We become gluttons.

20
00:02:48,353 --> 00:02:55,058
This tightrope distinguishing between what the body needs as opposed to what the mind greeds is the middle path.

21
00:02:56,520 --> 00:03:03,887
It helps us to purify the mind of gross appetites and emotions and to establish a peaceful disposition contented

22
00:03:05,402 --> 00:03:12,691
But this middle path also suggests a hierarchy, an apex of a triangle which transcends the two points on either side of the base.

23
00:03:14,012 --> 00:03:23,662
When insight is gained into nibbana, then we can say that by destroying the very roots of our discontent, the path now completely transcends the other two.

24
00:03:24,302 --> 00:03:32,270
And indeed, that is one way of describing the Buddhist saint or arahat, one who is beyond self-indulgence and self-mortification.

25
00:03:34,799 --> 00:03:38,705
The Noble Eightfold Path, the Middle Path, is laid out in this order.

26
00:03:39,987 --> 00:03:45,318
The first two, Right Understanding and Right Intention, come under the division of Wisdom.

27
00:03:46,620 --> 00:03:51,027
Right Speech, Right Action and Right Livelihood come under the division of Morality.

28
00:03:52,150 --> 00:03:57,819
Right Effort, Right Mindfulness and Right Concentration come under the division of Mental Development.

29
00:03:58,963 --> 00:04:06,050
However, in later talks, the Buddha turns his presentation around to show how the theory is put into practice.

30
00:04:07,151 --> 00:04:11,135
There is a passage cropping up time and time again at the end of the discourses.

31
00:04:12,217 --> 00:04:19,805
We have to remember those were the days before cassette recorders, videos and even books, news travelled by word of mouth and slowly.

32
00:04:20,906 --> 00:04:28,312
As the Buddha wandered around the area of North India, around the Ganges, he had to constantly repeat the message.

33
00:04:28,934 --> 00:04:37,286
All discourses have some nuance to add to the teaching, but many of them end with what must have been one of his most well-known formula.

34
00:04:39,511 --> 00:04:44,057
Such is morality, such is mental development, such is wisdom.

35
00:04:45,038 --> 00:04:49,666
Mental development, when based on morality, is rich in result and of great effect.

36
00:04:50,829 --> 00:04:56,156
Wisdom, based on mental development, is rich in result and great in effect.

37
00:04:58,836 --> 00:05:02,482
In the Buddha's understanding, morality is the key to further development.

38
00:05:03,423 --> 00:05:06,726
So we shall concentrate on the meaning of morality and its importance.

39
00:05:07,468 --> 00:05:09,350
Here we will deal with the negative aspect.

40
00:05:09,911 --> 00:05:13,134
Positive morality, virtue, will be dealt with next time.

41
00:05:15,819 --> 00:05:20,504
Morality these days is still something of a dirty word with heavy Victorian overtones.

42
00:05:21,266 --> 00:05:26,312
Behind this sits the notion of an angry deity who judges and punishes every transgression.

43
00:05:27,406 --> 00:05:47,850
To understand Buddhist morality, we have to keep in mind that first, there is no such concept of a punishing or rewarding God, and secondly, that morality is bound up with the law of cause and effect, karma, which states that what is wholesome produces wholesomeness, and what is unwholesome produces unwholesomeness.

44
00:05:49,031 --> 00:05:57,261
So, on one level, morality is about our actions in the world, realizing that our actions are producing effects all the time,

45
00:05:58,303 --> 00:06:09,139
If this is so, we need to know what sort of action brings about a good result and happy peaceful situations, and what sort of action brings about painful situations and happy results.

46
00:06:11,302 --> 00:06:14,526
On another level, morality is about our state of mind within.

47
00:06:15,307 --> 00:06:19,533
According to the law of karma, it is our wills that produce our states of mind.

48
00:06:20,434 --> 00:06:27,163
It is by willing to think about and so produce acts of generosity and compassion that loving states of mind arise.

49
00:06:27,869 --> 00:06:35,940
It is by willing to think about my personal benefit at the expense of others that brings about the selfish, jealous, anxious states of mind.

50
00:06:38,324 --> 00:06:43,891
On one level then, the moral laws in Buddhism are about creating a peaceful and caring society.

51
00:06:44,473 --> 00:06:46,555
They are the basis for real social harmony.

52
00:06:47,276 --> 00:06:55,108
On the other hand, they are laws of mental health, which when followed, create a mind full of compassion, joy and peace.

53
00:06:56,589 --> 00:07:01,317
The simplest formulation made by the Buddha is recorded in the discourses in verse.

54
00:07:02,779 --> 00:07:07,208
Cease from harm, do good, purify the mind.

55
00:07:08,088 --> 00:07:10,413
This is the teaching of all the Buddhas.

56
00:07:13,377 --> 00:07:15,581
We can call these three the primary precepts.

57
00:07:16,242 --> 00:07:22,192
The first is the negative morality, what we ought not to do by way of harm to ourselves and others.

58
00:07:22,779 --> 00:07:27,788
The second is the positive morality, what we ought to do for our benefit and the benefit of all beings.

59
00:07:28,829 --> 00:07:35,040
The third is to do with clearing out all negative tendencies in the mind and replacing them with positive attitudes.

60
00:07:37,846 --> 00:07:41,391
So what is the Buddha's formulation of cease from evil in detail?

61
00:07:42,434 --> 00:07:46,240
What are those thoughts, words and actions which produce unwholesome states?

62
00:07:47,637 --> 00:07:54,343
They are known as the ten wrong actions and they are split into three divisions, wrong thought, wrong speech and wrong action.

63
00:07:56,365 --> 00:08:02,050
Wrong thought takes up the first three of the ten, avarice, ill will and wrong views.

64
00:08:03,350 --> 00:08:09,896
Avarice is to do with all those fantasies and mental projects we indulge that have their motivation in greed.

65
00:08:10,896 --> 00:08:16,141
Self-indulgent, lustful, selfish thoughts, fantasies of wealth, fame and power.

66
00:08:16,762 --> 00:08:19,367
It's the mentality of accumulation, of acquisition.

67
00:08:20,869 --> 00:08:26,778
Ill will includes all those thoughts based on hatred, from jealousy to anger, from grudge to revenge.

68
00:08:28,401 --> 00:08:34,429
Wrong views here means our tendency to indulge in what is harmful, kidding ourselves that it isn't so.

69
00:08:35,412 --> 00:08:39,597
It means especially not understanding or knowing the Lord of Karma.

70
00:08:40,995 --> 00:08:47,184
In this negative morality, this means that unskillful behavior necessarily brings unhappy results.

71
00:08:48,788 --> 00:08:54,917
It includes the conceit that our opinions are always right, even when they are obviously getting us into trouble.

72
00:08:56,118 --> 00:09:00,625
It demands we check all our opinions in the light of our own experience and the experience of others.

73
00:09:01,515 --> 00:09:11,086
The kernel of wrong view, in terms of the ten wrong actions, is to believe that since we've got away with some unskillful behaviour, that that's the end of the story.

74
00:09:13,549 --> 00:09:16,413
Wrong speech takes up the next four of the wrong actions.

75
00:09:16,812 --> 00:09:19,216
The first is lying, saying anything untrue.

76
00:09:20,017 --> 00:09:25,363
For those of finer conscience, it includes what is often euphemistically called exaggeration.

77
00:09:27,081 --> 00:09:32,246
The second is malicious talk, which only furthers backbiting and disharmony.

78
00:09:33,048 --> 00:09:36,471
Slander often joins together lying and malicious talk.

79
00:09:38,373 --> 00:09:42,037
The third is coarse speech, the use of four-letter words and so on.

80
00:09:43,238 --> 00:09:47,042
We need to ask what sort of mental state lies behind the use of such words.

81
00:09:48,102 --> 00:09:50,144
Finally, useless talk, idle gossip.

82
00:09:50,865 --> 00:09:57,072
Again, we are looking at the state of mind indulged in, the whinging, complaining, bored, empty, rattling mind

83
00:09:59,548 --> 00:10:08,644
There is a quaint story attached to one of the verses spoken by the Buddha in the Dhammapada, which is the collection of the Buddha's sayings.

84
00:10:08,663 --> 00:10:12,410
A certain Tambadatika had been the king's executioner for 45 years.

85
00:10:13,452 --> 00:10:19,562
He had retired and had asked one of the Buddha's chief disciples, Sariputta, to receive alms food at his home.

86
00:10:20,784 --> 00:10:23,288
Sariputta was one of the two chief disciples of the Buddha.

87
00:10:23,730 --> 00:10:25,572
He was known as the general of the Dhamma.

88
00:10:27,072 --> 00:10:34,219
After he had eaten, the elder gave a talk about the Dharma, but he could see that Tambadataka was very agitated and unable to concentrate.

89
00:10:35,740 --> 00:10:41,105
Tambadataka explained that memories of all the deaths he had caused as executioner was the reason for his agitation.

90
00:10:42,067 --> 00:10:46,831
Sariputta asked him if he was the one who had decided they had to be executed.

91
00:10:47,932 --> 00:10:52,557
He said that that had been the king's work, and that he himself had never really wanted to kill anyone.

92
00:10:53,378 --> 00:10:55,779
He had done so because he was ordered to.

93
00:10:56,332 --> 00:10:57,294
He had had no option.

94
00:10:58,899 --> 00:11:07,139
Sariputta told him that if that were so, he was not guilty of murder as such, since it had never been his intention to execute the condemned.

95
00:11:08,240 --> 00:11:10,506
Tambadataka was greatly relieved in his heart.

96
00:11:11,288 --> 00:11:14,375
That same afternoon, it seems, he was accidentally killed by a cow.

97
00:11:15,537 --> 00:11:28,197
When the Buddha heard of this, he said that although Tambadatika had followed an unwholesome profession, because of the Dharma he had heard, he had been reborn in a place where he would be able to handle the results of his actions much better.

98
00:11:29,118 --> 00:11:33,504
Then he uttered this verse concerning the teaching of the Dharma.

99
00:11:33,524 --> 00:11:43,400
Better than a thousand words that are senseless and unconnected with the realization of Nibbana is a single word of sense if upon hearing it one is calmed.

100
00:11:45,827 --> 00:11:48,931
These days this concept of useless talk is very much overlooked.

101
00:11:49,390 --> 00:11:56,278
If we examine our media, the TV programs, the serials, soap operas and the newspapers, so much of it is filling our minds with hogwash.

102
00:11:56,998 --> 00:11:57,458
Don't you think?

103
00:11:59,880 --> 00:12:01,322
Finally, there's wrong action.

104
00:12:01,722 --> 00:12:02,504
The final three.

105
00:12:03,303 --> 00:12:07,628
The first is not to kill any living being, and it also includes not doing them harm.

106
00:12:08,889 --> 00:12:14,754
The second is not to steal, which is phrased as not taking what is not freely given.

107
00:12:16,321 --> 00:12:22,049
The third is sensual misconduct, such as gluttony, drunkenness and self-indulgent sexuality.

108
00:12:23,251 --> 00:12:26,197
These days the whole area of sexuality is very confused.

109
00:12:26,717 --> 00:12:30,884
There are fundamental Christian sex, for whom sex is a bad thing in itself.

110
00:12:31,765 --> 00:12:38,937
And there is the libertine view that their personal freedom to satisfy any desire means virtually a right to sex on demand.

111
00:12:40,267 --> 00:12:44,070
Interestingly, the occasion of AIDS has brought about a rethink of sorts.

112
00:12:44,650 --> 00:12:50,635
One can only hope it is not going to result in a vindictive witch hunt and a return to the bad old days of repression.

113
00:12:52,837 --> 00:12:57,942
In traditional Buddhist countries, sexual activity is seen as something limited within the bonds of marriage.

114
00:12:58,823 --> 00:13:07,692
In the West, since there is no general consensus, it is best left to the individual to decide what is unskillful and what is skillful in such behaviour.

115
00:13:09,157 --> 00:13:16,048
These are some of the questions that a Buddhist perspective would want to ask What is the reason for the sexual pleasure?

116
00:13:17,090 --> 00:13:18,412
Is it just self-indulgence?

117
00:13:19,393 --> 00:13:22,138
Is there any real affection involved in the relationship?

118
00:13:23,019 --> 00:13:24,000
Is it just habitual?

119
00:13:25,062 --> 00:13:27,966
Are the factors of reproduction being taken into account?

120
00:13:30,049 --> 00:13:33,054
The fundamental guiding principle is that of not doing harm

121
00:13:33,996 --> 00:13:42,889
No matter how important sexual pleasure may have become to us in our culture, we need to investigate and see what is the outcome of all this sexual activity.

122
00:13:44,091 --> 00:13:47,195
What is the effect both within the mind and between people?

123
00:13:48,196 --> 00:13:50,479
We need to be quite truthful about it to ourselves.

124
00:13:51,120 --> 00:13:56,206
We need to be prepared to change if our experience and understanding asks for a change in behaviour.

125
00:13:57,368 --> 00:14:04,096
It is surprising, for instance, how many smokers will still say that the link between tobacco and cancer is not yet proved conclusively.

126
00:14:04,878 --> 00:14:06,679
Surely a warning signal should be enough.

127
00:14:07,360 --> 00:14:12,988
But such is the dependency, the craving, that people will kid themselves along, even to death.

128
00:14:15,831 --> 00:14:23,562
These ten wrong actions give us, in some detail, what the Buddha meant by right speech and right action in the Noble Eightfold Path.

129
00:14:24,740 --> 00:14:31,730
There is also included here part of right intention, and all of it naturally is included in right livelihood.

130
00:14:33,133 --> 00:14:41,166
It is interesting that the Buddha was all too aware of how much our jobs and work dominate our lives, how they affect our minds and social relationships.

131
00:14:42,388 --> 00:14:52,283
Wrong livelihood is really an extension of wrong speech and wrong action, but it did give the Buddha the opportunity to pinpoint some traits which he said ought not to be practiced.

132
00:14:53,157 --> 00:15:20,784
they will not come as any surprise to you dealing in arms and lethal weapons dealing in animal slaughter dealing in human beings these days we might consider slave wages making and selling intoxicating beverages we can also include here the whole drug trade and finally dealing in poisons including chemical and germ warfare of today if we end up doing such work

133
00:15:21,506 --> 00:15:26,813
It is good to refer to the story of Tambadatika, so that we are not worried by false guilts and anxieties.

134
00:15:28,216 --> 00:15:39,152
If we find ourselves doing any job of work, which we come to realise is harmful and we wish to leave, it is good to take into account all the consequences of such a move, such as effect upon income and family.

135
00:15:40,113 --> 00:15:44,219
It may mean we have to stay in such work until other opportunities arise.

136
00:15:45,520 --> 00:15:48,004
Our search for other occupation must be vigorous, mind.

137
00:15:48,490 --> 00:15:54,118
And in the meantime, we can take solace in the fact that our intentions are no longer to do harm.

138
00:15:54,980 --> 00:15:55,880
This takes patience.

139
00:15:56,461 --> 00:15:59,326
It means accepting one's karma, one's actual situation.

140
00:16:00,287 --> 00:16:06,395
It's of little help to take a lofty moralistic position, which of course is what people outside the situation often do.

141
00:16:08,139 --> 00:16:17,011
The relief comes in the fact that once we have left such unwholesome work, upon the leaving, no more unwholesome karma is being created.

142
00:16:20,434 --> 00:16:23,659
Finally, a word about lay practice in Theravada tradition.

143
00:16:25,022 --> 00:16:28,687
All lay Buddhists take what's called the Five Precepts as training rules.

144
00:16:29,788 --> 00:16:32,552
It is important to remember that the Buddha was not prescriptive.

145
00:16:33,414 --> 00:16:35,658
These aren't commandments with attached penalties.

146
00:16:36,639 --> 00:16:42,128
These are rules of conduct, which are the first step on the path leading to the purification of the mind.

147
00:16:43,250 --> 00:16:46,695
They are training rules lay Buddhists take upon themselves.

148
00:16:47,299 --> 00:16:56,312
They try to keep them as best they can, though of course there will be times lack of attentiveness or lack of willpower will cause them to break the training rules.

149
00:16:57,554 --> 00:16:58,716
They are phrased as follows.

150
00:17:00,197 --> 00:17:15,400
I undertake the training rule to refrain from harming any living being, taking what is not freely given, misusing the senses, wrong speech, taking drugs or drinks that tend to cloud the mind.

151
00:17:18,113 --> 00:17:22,537
Finally, it is necessary to discuss the role of guilt, sorrow and penance in Buddhism.

152
00:17:23,759 --> 00:17:32,307
Guilt is simply the knowledge that we have done something wrong and usually accompanying this insight are the feelings of shame and fear of the consequences.

153
00:17:33,769 --> 00:17:35,349
This in Buddhism is quite proper.

154
00:17:35,369 --> 00:17:45,099
Feeling sorry, however, is only wholesome if it leads to the resolution to put right what is wrong and to resolve not to do such a thing again.

155
00:17:46,327 --> 00:17:50,432
If, for instance, I've given somebody a bad name, I'm guilty of doing harm.

156
00:17:51,374 --> 00:17:53,175
I'm afraid the person will find out.

157
00:17:53,776 --> 00:17:55,097
I'm ashamed of what I've done.

158
00:17:57,079 --> 00:18:00,544
Acknowledging this, I tell others I was wrong to say what I said.

159
00:18:01,684 --> 00:18:04,388
I might even feel it necessary to tell the wronged person.

160
00:18:05,910 --> 00:18:09,213
Having done this, I resolve not to slander again.

161
00:18:10,442 --> 00:18:20,212
If shame and fear keep on arising, I should just observe this, especially in meditation, and remind myself that these feelings are the unwholesome results of unskillful action.

162
00:18:21,494 --> 00:18:23,517
In that way they become great teachers for us.

163
00:18:24,978 --> 00:18:33,968
I should remind myself that I have done what I can to put things right, that I will without doubt have to accept the consequences of what I've done.

164
00:18:35,209 --> 00:18:38,813
Indulging these feelings of shame or fear produces neurosis.

165
00:18:39,721 --> 00:18:41,843
it is best not to give them any importance.

166
00:18:43,585 --> 00:18:57,200
Now as for penance, if it means piling more suffering on top of myself as punishment, then according to the Buddha, this is not only unnecessary, it could be harmful, in that it might develop cruel and self-destructive tendencies.

167
00:18:59,041 --> 00:19:04,728
Whether I like it or not, because of the Lord of Karma, I will reap the sour fruits of my action.

168
00:19:05,288 --> 00:19:06,048
Isn't that enough?

169
00:19:07,243 --> 00:19:19,636
What I must do to sweeten these fruits a little is to put an end as best I can to the effects of my wrong speech, determine never to slander again, and resolve to cultivate an attitude of seeing the best in people.

170
00:19:21,479 --> 00:19:27,464
In this way the Buddha has given directions as to how to start on the Noble Eightfold Path, leading to the end of suffering.

171
00:19:28,886 --> 00:19:30,888
We need to purify our habits.

172
00:19:31,595 --> 00:19:38,962
This moral code is a set of guidelines that help us to rid ourselves of such unwholesome habits of thought, speech and action.

173
00:19:40,104 --> 00:19:46,811
We need to couple this with the practice of positive morality virtue, and this is formulated in Buddhism as the Ten Perfections.

174
00:19:48,012 --> 00:19:56,542
In this way, the foundation is laid for mental development and insight wisdom, the experience of the end of suffering, nibbana.

175
00:19:59,105 --> 00:20:00,386
Well, I hope you found this talk useful.

176
00:20:01,243 --> 00:20:02,367
Interesting and helpful?

177
00:20:03,731 --> 00:20:05,557
May all of you be happy and peaceful.

178
00:20:06,601 --> 00:20:09,549
May all of you attain the nirvanic peace within.

